'''The President's Commission on Enhancing National Cybersecurity''' is a [[Presidential Commission (United States)|Presidential Commission]] formed April 13, 2016 to develop a plan for protecting cyberspace, and America's economic reliance on it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2016/04/13/announcing-presidents-commission-enhancing-national-cybersecurity|title=Announcing the President’s Commission on Enhancing National Cybersecurity|website=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2016-04-14}}</ref><ref>''The Commission will make detailed short-term and long-term recommendations to strengthen cybersecurity in both the public and private sectors, while protecting privacy, ensuring public safety and economic and national security, fostering discovery and development of new technical solutions, and bolstering partnerships between Federal, State, and local government and the private sector in the development, promotion, and use of cybersecurity technologies, policies, and best practices.'' {{Executive Order|13718}} of February 9, 2016 {{Cite web|title=Commission on Enhancing National Cybersecurity |publisher=National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) |url=https://www.nist.gov/cybercommission |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122005136/https://www.nist.gov/cybercommission |archivedate=22 November 2016 |deadurl=no}}</ref> The commission released its final report in December 2016. The report made recommendations regarding the intertwining roles of the military, government administration and the private sector in providing cyber security.<ref name="Rockwell">{{Cite magazine|last=Rockwell |first=Mark |date=21 November 2016 |title=Cyber panel closes in on final recommendations |magazine=Federal Computer Week (FCW) |publisher=1105 Media, Inc. |url=https://fcw.com/articles/2016/11/21/cnap-commission-report-rockwell.aspx |accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> Chairman Donilon said of the report that its coverage "is unusual in the breadth of issues" with which it deals.<ref name="Rockwell" />
==Recommendations== The report made sixteen major recommendations with fifty-three specific action items broadly grouped under six areas:<ref name="HW">{{Cite web|title=Commission on Enhancing National Cybersecurity Issues Recommendations |date=5 December 2016 |publisher=Hunton & Williams’ Global Privacy and Cybersecurity Law |url=https://www.huntonprivacyblog.com/2016/12/05/commission-enhancing-national-cybersecurity-issues-recommendations/ |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6oD9xHbBL?url=https://www.huntonprivacyblog.com/2016/12/05/commission-enhancing-national-cybersecurity-issues-recommendations/ |archive-date=12 February 2017 |deadurl=no}}</ref> # Protecting the information and digital infrastructure # Investing in the secure growth of information and digital infrastructure # Consumer information access # Building the cybersecurity workforce # Building a secure governmental cybersecurity framework # Keeping interconnectivity open, fair, competitive, and secure
The Commission found that strong authentication systems were mandatory for adequate cybersecurity, not just for the government, but for all commercial systems, and private individuals.<ref name="FIDO">{{Cite web |last=McDowell |first=Brett |date=5 December 2016 |title=US Commission on Enhancing National Cybersecurity Calls for an End to Password-based Breaches by 2021, Highlights the Importance of FIDO Standards |publisher=Fast IDentity Online (FIDO) Alliance |url=https://fidoalliance.org/us-commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity-calls-for-an-end-to-password-based-breaches-by-2021/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130072349/https://fidoalliance.org/us-commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity-calls-for-an-end-to-password-based-breaches-by-2021/ |archive-date=30 January 2017 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> The commission also stressed remote identity proofing and security for the [[Internet of things]] (IoT).<ref name="FIDO" /><ref name="Wright">{{Cite web |last=Wright |first=Helen |date=6 February 2017 |title=Research Implications of the Report from the President’s Commission on Enhancing National Cybersecurity |work=Research News |publisher=Computing Community Consortium (CCC) |url=http://www.cccblog.org/2017/02/06/research-implications-of-the-report-from-the-presidents-commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212024524/http://www.cccblog.org/2017/02/06/research-implications-of-the-report-from-the-presidents-commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity/ |archive-date=12 February 2017 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> Finding that technicians who know cybersecurity and can protect systems are few and in short supply, the commission recommended nationally supported training programs to produce an adequate workforce, as well as increasing the level of expertise in the existing workforce.<ref name="Burgess">{{Cite web |last=Burgess |first=Christopher |date=12 December 2016 |title=President’s Commission on Enhancing National Cybersecurity Recommendations |publisher=ClearanceJobs |url=https://news.clearancejobs.com/2016/12/12/presidents-commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity-recommendations/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212032605/https://news.clearancejobs.com/2016/12/12/presidents-commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity-recommendations/ |archive-date=12 February 2017 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref><ref name="CNN-1">{{Cite news|last=Pagliery |first=Jose |date=2 December 2016 |title=Panel to Trump: Train 100,000 hackers |publisher=CNN |url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/12/02/technology/commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204013918/http://money.cnn.com/2016/12/02/technology/commission-on-enhancing-national-cybersecurity/ |archive-date=4 December 2016 |deadurl=no}}</ref> The Commission highlighted the importance of partnerships between government and the private sector as ''a powerful tool for encouraging the technology, policies and practices we need to secure and grow the digital economy.'' (page 2)<ref name="FIDO" />
Some<ref>For example, the CEO of Errata Security, in his article {{Cite web |last=Graham |first=Robert |date=5 December 2016 |title=The ‘Commission on Cyber Security’ is absurd |publisher=Errata Security |url=http://blog.erratasec.com/2016/12/that-commission-on-enhancing.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222181848/http://blog.erratasec.com/2016/12/that-commission-on-enhancing.html |archive-date=22 December 2016 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> criticised the commission's work as lacking an understanding of cybersecurity and not being cognizant of "cyber reality"<ref>Among other things, how IoT devices work. {{harvnb|Graham|2016}}</ref> and the cost of some of the action items, but others found the report constructive and meaningful.<ref name="HW" /><ref name="Burgess" />
==Commission members== The initial members of the Commission are: * [[Tom Donilon]], former Assistant to the President and National Security Advisor (Chair) * [[Sam Palmisano]], former CEO of IBM (Vice Chair) * General [[Keith B. Alexander|Keith Alexander]], CEO of IronNet Cybersecurity, former Director of the National Security Agency and former Commander of U.S. Cyber Command * [[Annie Antón]], Professor and Chair of the School of Interactive Computing at Georgia Tech. * [[Ajay Banga]], President and CEO of MasterCard * [[Steven Chabinsky]], General Counsel and Chief Risk Officer of CrowdStrike * [[Patrick D. Gallagher|Patrick Gallagher]], Chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh and former Director of the National Institute of Standards and Technology * [[Peter Lee (computer scientist)|Peter Lee]], Corporate Vice President, Microsoft Research * [[Herbert Lin]], Senior Research Scholar for Cyber Policy and Security at the Stanford Center for International Security and Cooperation and Research Fellow at the Hoover Institution * [[Heather Murren]], former member of the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission and co-founder of the Nevada Cancer Institute * [[Joe Sullivan (security expert)|Joe Sullivan]], Chief Security Officer of Uber and former Chief Security Officer of Facebook * [[Maggie Wilderotter]], Executive Chairman of Frontier Communications
==Follow-on== Incoming President Trump has indicated that he wants a full review of U.S. cyber protection policy.<ref>{{Cite web|first=John |last=Costello |date=10 November 2016 |title=Overview of President-Elect Donald Trump’s Cyber Policy |publisher=Flashpoint |url=https://www.flashpoint-intel.com/overview-trumps-cyber-policy/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122192135/https://www.flashpoint-intel.com/overview-trumps-cyber-policy/ |archivedate=22 November 2016 |deadurl=no}}</ref>
