[[File:Cricetus_cricetus_front_foot.jpg|thumb|200px|Manus of a rodent, Eurasian hamster ''[[Cricetus cricetus]]'']]
The '''[[wikt:manus#Latin|manus]]''' ([[Latin language|Latin]] for ''[[hand]]'') is the [[Zoology|zoological]] term for the [[Anatomical terms of location#Proximal and distal|distal]] portion of the fore limb of an animal. In [[tetrapod]]s, it is the part of the [[pentadactyl limb]] that includes the [[metacarpal]]s and digits ([[Phalanx bones|phalanges]]). During [[evolution]], it has taken many forms and served a variety of functions. It can be represented by the hand of [[primate]]s, the lower front limb of hoofed animals or the fore paw and is represented in the wing of [[bird]]s, [[bat]]s and prehistoric flying reptiles ([[pterosaur]]s), the flipper of marine [[mammal]]s and the 'paddle' of [[Extinction|extinct]] marine [[reptile]]s, such as [[plesiosaur]]s and [[ichthyosaur]]s.

In [[cephalopods]], the ''manus'' is the end, broader part of a tentacle or arm, and its [[sucker (cephalopod anatomy)|suckers]] are often larger and arranged differently from those on the rest of the arm.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7N1j-8LMsEC&pg=PA277&dq=Manus+%28zoology%29&hl=en&ei=HLAUTcfVFMSblgeputDgCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CFIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Manus&f=false|title=Modern Text Book of Zoology: Vertebrates|last=Prof. R.L.Kotpal|publisher=Rastogi Publications|year=2009|isbn=81-7133-891-7|location=Meerut, New Delhi, India|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509183158/https://books.google.com/books?id=U7N1j-8LMsEC#v=onepage&q=Manus&f=false|archivedate=2016-05-09|df=}} </ref>

