The '''universal relation assumption''' in [[relational databases]] states, that one can place all data attributes into a (possibly very wide) table, which may then be decomposed into smaller tables as needed.<ref>[[Igor Hawryszkiewycz|I. T. Hawryszkiewycz]], ''Database analysis and design,'' 1984. {{ISBN|0-574-21485-2}}, pages 59-62.</ref>
However, the assumption that a single large table can capture real database designs is often plagued with a number of difficulties.<ref>Carlo Zaniolo, ''Advances in database technology--EDBT 2000,'' 2000. {{ISBN|3-540-67227-3}}, page 276</ref> The "nested universal relation" model has attempted to address some of the problems and offer improvements.<ref>Mark Levene, ''The nested universal relation database model,'' 2000. {{ISBN|3-540-55493-9}}, pages 1-5.</ref>
